            <p><hi rend="underline">COPY</hi></p>
            
            <p>Rev. Dr. B. Felsenthal<lb/>
                Philadelphia&#44; August 2nd&#44; 1889<lb/></p>
                
            <p>My dear Sir and Friend<lb/></p>
            <p>I thank you for the kind manner in which you saw<lb/> fit to mention my name relatively to your interesting article.  I must<lb/> freely acknowledge that with regard to the biennial cycle&#44; notwithstanding<lb/> your apologetic explanation &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> Still&#44; you are correct&#44; in the main&#44; that the absence of anterior and<lb/> posterior &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#40;as far as my limited knowledge goes&#41; to whom we<lb/> may refer in support of &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; causes his assertion. &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>What struck me forcibly is my having found that &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> there are only &#91;Hebrew&#93; viz 1&#41; &#91;Hebrew&#93; 2&#41; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> Indeed the Italian ritual&#44; which I consider the oldest is&#44; in many<lb/> respects&#44; so peculiar that scholars ought to make it a study.<lb/></p>
            <p>I was much interested also&#44; in your review of Finn&#39;s &#34;Hebrew<lb/> Dictionary&#34;.  It seems to me that the good man has undertaken<lb/> a herculean task &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  If he accomplishes it &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; I don&#39;t feel sure that the rest of the saying will apply.<lb/>  <sic>Neverlesless</sic> it must be gratefully confessed that there is a wakening<lb/> about Hebrew Literature&#44; notably so among <hi rend="underline">non</hi> Israelites.  Respecting<lb/> my sonnet allow me to remark that I did not give it a heading.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93; appears to define your meaning.  Graber took liberties with these<lb/> lines of mine &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  I had written it originally for the<lb/> Hebrew Standard&#44; at the end of an English article&#44; calling attention<lb/> to the promised &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/></p>
            <p>I was under the impression that &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> was the first Grammarian.  You have instructed me.  I never heard<lb/> of &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#40;Alam&#63;&#41;  With fraternal greetings<lb/> Yours Sincerely&#44; S. MORAIS<lb/></p>
            </body>
